  - Using the combinations formula $\binom{n}{r}=\tfrac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}$ we can rewrite both the LHS and the RHS of the equation

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        2\left(\dfrac{\cancel{n!}}{r!(n-r)!}\right)&=\dfrac{\cancel{n!}}{(r+1)!(n-(r+1))!}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Now we can simplify and rearrange the equation

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \dfrac{2(r+1)!}{r!}&=\dfrac{(n-r)!}{(n-r-1)!}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    Rewrite the numerators using the concept $n!=n(n-1)!$

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \dfrac{2(r+1)r!}{r!}&=\dfrac{(n-r)(n-r-1)!}{(n-r-1)!} \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{M1}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    We can cancel out the factorial terms

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        \dfrac{2(r+1)\cancel{r!}}{\cancel{r!}}&=\dfrac{(n-r)\cancel{(n-r-1)!}}{\cancel{(n-r-1)!}}\\[6pt]
        2(r+1)&=n-r\\[6pt]
        &\hspace{-2.8em} \tcbhighmath{3r+2=n} \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    As required.
  - Rewrite the equation using the combinations formula and simplify in a similar way to part (a)

    $$
    \begin{align*}
        7\left(\dfrac{n!}{(r-1)!(n-(r-1))!}\right)&=2\left(\dfrac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}\right)\\[6pt]
        \dfrac{7}{(r-1)!(n-r+1)!}&=\dfrac{2}{r!(n-r)!}\\[6pt]
        \dfrac{7r!}{(r-1)!}&=\dfrac{2(n-r+1)!}{(n-r)!}\\[6pt]
        \dfrac{7r\cancel{(r-1)!}}{\cancel{(r-1)!}}&=\dfrac{2(n-r+1)\cancel{(n-r)!}}{\cancel{(n-r)!}} \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{M1}}}\\[6pt]
        7r&=2n-2r+2\\[6pt]
        &\hspace{-2.8em} \tcbhighmath{9r-2=2n} \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
    \end{align*}
    $$

    As required.

- We can begin by expanding $(1+x)^n$, using the binomial theorem, in terms of $n$ and $r$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      (1+x)^n&=1+\binom{n}{1}x+\binom{n}{2}x^2+...\\[6pt]
      &\textcolor{red}{+\binom{n}{r-1}x^{r-1}+\binom{n}{r}x^r+\binom{n}{r+1}x^{r+1}+...}  \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}\\[6pt]
      &+x^n
  \end{align*}
  $$

  The terms in red represent any three consecutive terms in the expansion.
  We are told in the question the way in which the coefficients of three consecutive terms are related.

  $$
   \begin{align*}
  (1+x)^n=1+a_1x+...+\textcolor{red}{a_{k-1}x^{k-1}+a_{k}x^{k}+a_{k+1}x^{k+1}}+...+x^n
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  Hence we can use the information given to write the following two equations in terms of binomial coefficients

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &&7\times a_{k-1}&=2\times a_{k}& &&14\times a_{k}&=7\times a_{k+1}&  \\[6pt]
  &&7\binom{n}{r-1}&=2\binom{n}{r} &\hspace{-1em} && 14\binom{n}{r}&=7\binom{n}{r+1}& \\[6pt]
  &&&&\hspace{-1em} && 2\binom{n}{r}&=\binom{n}{r+1}& 
  \end{align*}
  $$

  In part (a) we already rewrote these equations without the combination notation, lets call them $[1]$ and $[2]$.
We can now solve them simultaneously and find $n$ and $r$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{M1}}}\\
      3r+2&=n \hspace{4.4em} [1]\\
      9r-2&=2n \hspace{4em} [2]\\
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Multiply $[1]$ by $3$ and subtract equation $[2]$ from this $\textcolor{red}{\text{result}}$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \textcolor{red}{9r}-9r+\textcolor{red}{6}-(-2)&=\textcolor{red}{3n}-2n\\[6pt]
      &\hspace{-0.6em}\tcbhighmath{n=8} \tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$
